@edition "2026.6"

-- D1(viii) frontier guardrail. This program is VALID (it type-checks clean — a `_test`,
-- not a `_bad`), but it names a BUILTIN (`abs`) as a value rather than calling it. eval
-- has this for free — a builtin is a VBuiltin in the environment, so `let f = abs`
-- captures it — and a *user* `def` reference now lowers too (D1(viii)). But a builtin is
-- not a user `def`: it has no `function` declaration in the emitted module, only an
-- inlined prelude `const`, and the lowerer's first-class-reference path admits user defs
-- ONLY (`userFns`). So a bare builtin name is an out-of-scope `Var` the lowerer refuses
-- as a free variable. The differential harness must report it `unsupported` — a CLEAN
-- refusal at the compiler frontier — never a miscompile, never a JS crash.
--
-- This is the backend-slice analogue of a `_bad` twin: a backend slice adds no checker
-- rejection rule, so the guarantee under test is "the compiler refuses what it cannot
-- yet lower, loudly", asserted by the harness rather than by an error count. D1(ii)
-- moved the frontier PAST scalar `match`; D1(iii) PAST tuples; D1(iv) PAST ADT
-- constructors; D1(v) PAST records; D1(vi) PAST lists; D1(vii) PAST closures-as-values;
-- D1(viii) PAST first-class `def` references — a named def bound, passed, returned, and
-- displayed `<fn:name>` (see compile_defref_test). The frontier now sits at FIRST-CLASS
-- BUILTIN references — naming a builtin as a value. This file binds one, so it still
-- refuses; when builtin references lower (a later D1 slice), it flips from `unsupported`
-- to a print with no edit.

def main(): Effect [io] ()
  let f = abs
  println(f(-7))
